You are helping the user commit and push changes to a Rust CLI project. Follow these steps exactly.

## Step 1 — Pre-commit checks (REQUIRED, never skip)

Run all three in sequence. Stop and fix any failures before continuing.

```
cargo fmt --check
cargo build
cargo test
```

If `cargo fmt --check` fails, run `cargo fmt` to fix it, then re-run the check.
If `cargo build` or `cargo test` fails, fix the underlying issue before committing.

## Step 2 — Understand the changes

Run these in parallel:
```
git status
git diff
git log --oneline -5
```

## Step 3 — Write the commit message

Follow **Conventional Commits**:

| Prefix | When |
|--------|------|
| `feat(scope):` | New command, flag, or user-visible feature |
| `fix(scope):` | Bug fix |
| `refactor(scope):` | Code cleanup, no behavior change |
| `chore:` | Dependencies, tooling, CI |
| `docs:` | README, comments, CLAUDE.md |
| `test:` | Adding or fixing tests |

- Scope is optional but encouraged: `feat(goto):`, `fix(update):`, etc.
- Keep the subject line under 72 characters
- Add `Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>` as a trailer

## Step 4 — Stage and commit

Stage only relevant files (never `git add -A` blindly — avoid `.env`, secrets, large binaries).

```bash
git add <specific files>
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
<type>(scope): <subject>

Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>
EOF
)"
```

## Step 5 — Push

```bash
git pull --rebase origin main && git push origin main
```

If push is rejected, rebase and retry once. If there are conflicts, resolve them and ask the user before force-pushing.

## PR label reminder

Every PR merged into `main` needs exactly one label: `major`, `minor`, or `patch`.
This drives the automatic version bump — default is `patch` if no label is set.
